  "rationale": "<p>Choice A is correct. The solution to a system of two linear equations is the point where the two lines intersect on the graph. From the graph, the two lines cross at the point (3, 5). Algebraically, setting the two right-hand sides equal gives 2x + (-1) = -1x + (8), which yields x = 3 and y = 5, confirming the intersection point.</p><p>The other choices identify other notable points (intercepts or nearby grid points), but only (3, 5) lies on both lines.</p>",
